making the code easier to manage and extend.âœ“In ASP.NET Core Razor Pages, the project structure is designed to follow the convention-over-configuration approach and is slightly different from MVC but still very organized.ğŸš€âœ“ ASP.Net Core Razor : - ğŸš€My .Net Core RazorAppğŸŒŸâ”‚â”œâ”€â”€ wwwroot     --> Static files (CSS, JS, images, etc.)â”‚â”œâ”€â”€ Pages                 --> Razor Pages (.cshtml + .cshtml.cs files)â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Shared            --> Layouts, Partial Views (e.g., _Layout.cshtml)â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Index.cshtml       --> Default home pageâ”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Index.cshtml.cs    --> PageModel (C# code-behind)â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ About.cshtml       --> Example of another Razor pageâ”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ About.cshtml.cs â”‚   â””â”€â”€ Error.cshtmlâ”‚â”œâ”€â”€ Models                --> C# classes representing your data models (e.g., User.cs, Product.cs)â”‚â”œâ”€â”€ Data                 --> DbContext, Repositories, Interfaces (optional if using repository pattern)â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ AppDbContext.csâ”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ IRepository.csâ”‚   â””â”€â”€ Repository.csâ”‚â”œâ”€â”€ Services        --> Business logic or service classes (optional)â”‚â”œâ”€â”€ obj       --> Auto-generated files during buildâ”‚â”œâ”€â”€ bin           --> Compiled outputâ”‚â”œâ”€â”€ appsettings.json       --> Application settings (connection strings, config values)â”œâ”€â”€ Program.cs     --> Main entry pointâ”œâ”€â”€ Startup.cs      --> Middleware & service registration (for .NET Core 3.1 and earlier) or moved to Program.cs in .NET 6+â”œâ”€â”€ MyRazorApp.csproj      --> Project fileâ”‚â””â”€â”€ Properties â””â”€â”€ launchSettings.json --> Debugging and launch settingsâ€¢ This structure ensures clear separation of concerns making the code more manageable and scalable over time.âœ¨ğŸ“ Contact:ğŸ“§ rakeshmorichauhan777@gmail.comğŸŒ Portfolio#Asp.Net #.NetDev hashtag#MVC hashtag#Core hashtag#WebApis #C# hashtag#Microsoft SQL Server hashtag#Oracle hashtag#Developer hashtag#Web hashtag#Cross hashtag#Github hashtag#Git
